recalls.Summary: BMW North America, LLC (BMW) is recalling certain model year 2016 BMW M2 Coupe vehicles, 2015-2017 M3 Sedan vehicles and 2015-2016 M4 Coupe and M4 Convertible vehicles.  During servicing of the rear differential for a prior service action, the rear sub-frame bolts may have been reused instead of being replaced.  Reuse of the existing bolts may cause the bolts to loosen.
recalls.Consequence: Loose rear sub-frame bolts may adversely affect vehicle handling and control, increasing the risk of a crash.
recalls.Remedy: BMW will notify owners, and dealers will replace the rear sub-frame bolts with new bolts, free of charge.  The recall began on November 3, 2016.  Owners may contact BMW customer service at 1-800-525-7417.
recalls.Notes: Owners may also contact the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration Vehicle Safety Hotline at 1-888-327-4236 (TTY 1-800-424-9153), or go to www.safercar.gov.

recalls.Summary: BMW of North America, LLC (BMW) is recalling certain model year 2015-2016 M3 Sedan vehicles manufactured May 30, 2015, to September 2, 2015, 2016 M4 Coupe vehicles manufactured July 3, 2015, to September 11, 2015, and 2015-2016 M4 Convertible vehicles manufactured May 29, 2015, to August 4, 2015. The affected vehicles have a driveshaft with a slip-joint that may not have been filled with grease.  As a result, the slip-joint may fail over time.
recalls.Consequence: If the slip-joint fails, there would be a loss of power to the rear axle and therefore the vehicle would stop moving, increasing the risk of a crash.
recalls.Remedy: BMW will notify owners, and dealers will inspect the driveshaft, replacing it as necessary, free of charge.  The recall began on January 14, 2016.  Owners may contact BMW customer service at 1-800-525-7417.
recalls.Notes: Owners may also contact the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration Vehicle Safety Hotline at 1-888-327-4236 (TTY 1-800-424-9153), or go to www.safercar.gov.

recalls.Summary: BMW of North America, LLC (BMW) is recalling certain 2014-2015 2 Series Coupe (228i, 228i xDrive, M235i), 3 Series Sedan (320i, 320i xDrive, 328i, 328i xDrive, 335i, 335i xDrive, M3, 328d, 328d xDrive), 4 Series Coupe (428i, 428i xDrive, 435i, 435i xDrive, M4), and 2015 4 Series Gran Coupe (428i, 428i xDrive, 435i, 435i xDrive) vehicles.  The head air bag inflator may fail at the weld joint, which can cause gas to leak from the inflator or result in an inflator rupture.
recalls.Consequence: An inflator that ruptures may cause sharp metal fragments to enter or exit the vehicle, increasing the risk of injury.  Additionally, an inflator that leaks gas may only partially inflate during a crash, increasing the risk of injury.
recalls.Remedy: Dealers will replace the head air bags, free of charge.  Owner notification letters were mailed November 4, 2024.  Owners may contact BMW customer service at 1-800-525-7417.
recalls.Notes: Owners may also contact the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration Vehicle Safety Hotline at 1-888-327-4236 (TTY 1-800-424-9153), or go to www.nhtsa.gov.

issues.title: Main Bearing Issues and Rod Bearing Failure
issues.description: The S55 engine in the F80 M3 is prone to premature main and rod bearing wear, potentially leading to catastrophic engine failure. This issue is particularly common in high-mileage vehicles or those subjected to aggressive driving.
issues.fix_description: Complete engine rebuild or replacement with upgraded bearings
issues.prevention: Regular oil changes with high-quality oil, avoid extended high RPM operation, monitor oil analysis reports

issues.title: Crankshaft Hub Bolt Failure
issues.description: The crankshaft hub bolt can fail, causing the crankshaft pulley to separate and potentially destroying the engine timing. This is a known issue that BMW addressed with a technical service bulletin.
issues.fix_description: Replace crankshaft hub bolt with updated part and inspect for timing damage
issues.prevention: Have the crankshaft hub bolt inspected and replaced preventively during major service

issues.title: Carbon Buildup on Intake Valves
issues.description: Direct injection engines like the S55 are prone to carbon buildup on intake valves, leading to reduced performance and rough idle. This is exacerbated by the turbocharging system.
issues.fix_description: Walnut blasting or chemical cleaning of intake valves
issues.prevention: Use high-quality fuel, perform Italian tune-ups regularly, consider fuel system cleaners

issues.title: Turbocharger Wastegate Rattle
issues.description: The turbocharger wastegates can develop a rattling noise, particularly at idle or low RPM. This is caused by worn wastegate actuator arms or loose components within the turbocharger.
issues.fix_description: Replace turbocharger wastegate actuators or complete turbocharger replacement
issues.prevention: Regular oil changes, allow turbochargers to cool down after spirited driving

issues.title: Adaptive M Suspension Failure
issues.description: The electronic dampers in the Adaptive M Suspension can fail, causing harsh ride quality or complete suspension malfunction. This affects vehicles equipped with the optional adaptive suspension.
issues.prevention: Avoid harsh impacts, maintain proper tire pressure, regular suspension inspections

issues.title: Fuel Injector Failure
issues.description: Direct injection fuel injectors can fail or become clogged, leading to misfires and poor engine performance. This is common in high-mileage vehicles or those using poor-quality fuel.
issues.fix_description: Replace failed fuel injectors and perform fuel system cleaning
issues.prevention: Use high-quality fuel, regular fuel system cleaning, avoid running on empty

issues.title: Rear Differential Mount Failure
issues.description: The rear differential mounts can fail, causing excessive drivetrain noise and vibration. This is particularly common in vehicles with aggressive driving or track use.
issues.fix_description: Replace worn differential mounts with OEM or upgraded aftermarket units
issues.prevention: Avoid excessive wheelspin, regular drivetrain inspections

issues.title: VANOS System Problems
issues.description: The variable valve timing system can develop issues with solenoids or timing chains, affecting engine performance and potentially causing timing-related damage.
issues.fix_description: Replace VANOS solenoids, timing chains, or complete VANOS units as needed
issues.prevention: Regular oil changes with BMW-approved oil, avoid extended oil change intervals

issues.title: High Pressure Fuel Pump Failure
issues.description: The high pressure fuel pump can fail, causing fuel starvation and poor engine performance. This is critical for the direct injection system operation.
issues.fix_description: Replace high pressure fuel pump and related components
issues.prevention: Use quality fuel, avoid running fuel tank too low, regular fuel filter replacement

issues.title: Brake Pad and Rotor Wear
issues.description: The high-performance braking system experiences rapid wear, especially with spirited driving or track use. The large brake rotors and performance pads wear faster than standard vehicles.
issues.fix_description: Replace brake pads and rotors as needed
issues.prevention: Avoid riding brakes, proper cool-down after hard driving, regular brake inspections

issues.title: Electronic Power Steering Failure
issues.description: The electric power steering system can fail, resulting in heavy steering or complete loss of power assistance. This creates a significant safety concern.
issues.fix_description: Replace power steering motor or control unit
issues.prevention: Regular electrical system checks, avoid extreme steering lock positions

issues.title: Cooling System Issues
issues.description: Various cooling system components including water pumps, thermostats, and radiators can fail, potentially leading to overheating in the high-performance S55 engine.
issues.prevention: Regular coolant changes, avoid overheating, check coolant levels regularly

editorial.tagline: Turbocharged precision meets M Division fury
editorial.hero_blurb: The F80 M3 marked BMW's bold leap into forced induction for the M3 lineup, delivering explosive power through its twin-turbo S55 engine. This generation redefined what an M3 could be, blending daily usability with track-ready aggression in a package that's both civilized and savage.
editorial.essence: The F80 represents BMW's most controversial yet capable M3, trading the naturally aspirated wail of its predecessors for turbocharged torque and efficiency. It's a machine that can terrorize a track in the morning and ferry the family in the evening, embodying modern BMW M's philosophy of accessible performance.
editorial.heritage: Following the legendary E30, E36, E46, and E92 generations, the F80 broke tradition as the first turbocharged M3 sedan since the original E30. It carried forward 30 years of M3 DNA while embracing modern forced induction technology to meet emissions standards without sacrificing performance.
editorial.design_philosophy: BMW M designed the F80 to be the ultimate dual-personality machine - docile and efficient in Comfort mode, yet capable of unleashing 425 horsepower of fury when Sport+ is engaged. The goal was creating an M3 that could satisfy both purists and pragmatists.
editorial.motorsport_history: While not directly racing itself, the F80 shares DNA with BMW's successful turbocharged touring car programs. The S55 engine architecture influenced BMW's return to turbo racing applications, proving the viability of forced induction in motorsport contexts.
editorial.engine_character: The S55 twin-turbo inline-six delivers a Jekyll and Hyde personality - smooth and refined at low revs, then unleashing a tsunami of torque from 1850 RPM that builds relentlessly to redline. It's more brutally efficient than soulful, prioritizing devastating effectiveness over emotional appeal.
editorial.transmission_feel: The 6-speed manual offers mechanical precision with a satisfying throw, while the 7-speed DCT provides lightning-fast shifts that become increasingly aggressive in sportier modes. Both transmissions handle the S55's torque with confidence, though the DCT better exploits the engine's broad powerband.
editorial.chassis_dynamics: The F80's chassis is a masterclass in adaptability, featuring electronically controlled dampers that transform character on demand. In Comfort, it rides like a luxury sedan; in Sport+, it becomes a track-focused weapon with razor-sharp responses and minimal body roll.
editorial.steering_feel: The electrically assisted steering divides opinion - precise and quick but lacking the hydraulic feel of earlier M3s. While it provides accurate feedback and excellent on-center feel, purists miss the more organic connection of previous generations.
editorial.brake_confidence: Massive Brembo brakes provide phenomenal stopping power with excellent pedal feel and fade resistance. The braking system matches the car's dual personality, offering progressive feel for daily driving yet capable of repeated track abuse without complaint.
editorial.sound_signature: The S55 produces a distinctive growl that's more industrial than melodious - a purposeful rumble at idle that builds to an aggressive roar under full acceleration. While lacking the screaming soprano of naturally aspirated predecessors, it has its own menacing character amplified by turbo whoosh and wastegate chatter.
editorial.ideal_owner: Perfect for enthusiasts who want maximum performance with daily usability, track day warriors who need to drive home afterward, and those who appreciate engineering excellence over pure emotion. Ideal for drivers who value devastating capability over traditional M car soul.
editorial.not_ideal_for: Purists seeking the naturally aspirated M3 experience, those prioritizing emotional connection over clinical efficiency, or buyers wanting the most engaging steering feel. Also not suited for those expecting exotic car exclusivity or simple, analog driving dynamics.
editorial.buyers_summary: Look for well-maintained examples with service records, as the S55 engine and complex electronics require proper care. The F80 offers incredible performance per dollar but demands respect for its sophisticated systems and maintenance requirements.

expertReviews.title: BMW M3 F80 Review - Is It Still Great 10 Years On?
pros: Immediate turbo boost delivery feels like naturally aspirated engine with more torque
Manual transmission provides better control and predictable handling compared to dual clutch
Strong performance with 317kW/420hp and good power delivery to 7500 RPM
Excellent steering feel and predictable handling characteristics
Good value proposition in the 40k range used
Comprehensive feature set without feeling cluttered
cons: Interior plastic quality below expectations for price point
Rubbery and vague feeling manual gearbox
Controversial engine sound described as unusual and fake
Back seats are useless
Some build quality concerns compared to previous M3 generations
expertReviews.verdict: The F80 M3 with manual transmission is a sensational driver's car that overcomes its controversial reputation. Despite some interior quality issues and a rubbery gearbox feel, the immediate turbo delivery, predictable handling, and manual control make it a masterpiece. The reviewer would own one in a heartbeat, especially given the strong value proposition in the used market around 40k.

expertReviews.title: BMW F80 M3: 6 Month Ownership Review!
pros: Incredible power potential with simple mods
Raw driving feel compared to newer BMWs
Beautiful interior with leather package
Strong aftermarket support and community
Fast and responsive compared to Subaru platform
Versatile usage - daily driving, shows, track
cons: Front bumper sits extremely low - frequent lip damage
PCV valve failure around 60k miles
Gas cap locking mechanism issues
High fuel costs ($70-80 per tank in California)
Common crank hub preventative maintenance needed
expertReviews.verdict: After 6 months and 8,000 miles of ownership, the F80 M3 proves to be an excellent step up from Subaru platforms. While it has some common reliability issues like PCV valve failure and requires expensive preventative maintenance, the raw driving experience, massive power potential with bolt-ons, and beautiful interior make it worthwhile. The low front end is a constant annoyance, but overall it's a solid performance car that offers great value compared to newer BMW models.

expertReviews.title: BMW F80 M3 CS Review | The Best Modern M3 You Should ...
pros: Exceptional handling and dynamics compared to standard F80
Violent and engaging DCT shifts with character
460 hp with excellent power delivery and torque
Revised front geometry fixes standard F80 handling issues
Nurburgring lap time of 7:38 minutes
Limited production (1,200 units) collectible potential
Carbon fiber components including hood, roof, and splitter
Proper analog M gauges and driver-focused interior
Rear-wheel drive with engaging character
cons: Originally priced at $100,000 - significant premium over standard M3
No center armrest storage
Continental Cup 2 tires can be dangerous
Very stiff suspension
Limited availability when new
expertReviews.verdict: The F80 M3 CS is described as 'the last true M3' worth buying and represents the best version of the F80 generation. It fixes all the major complaints about the standard F80 (heavy steering, handling issues) with revised geometry, upgraded DCT programming, and enhanced dynamics. The reviewer emphasizes this car has the 'character' missing from newer G80 M3s, with violent shifts, proper feedback, and engaging driving experience. Compared favorably to Alfa Romeo Giulia QV for dynamics and described as having collectible potential like E46 M3 or E39 M5.

expertReviews.title: My BMW F80 M3 2 Year Ownership Review
pros: Exceptional looks - described as best looking M3 ever produced and best looking sports sedan from any brand
Excellent BMW M community support and camaraderie
Strong aftermarket support for modifications
Manual transmission option available for driver engagement
Versatile - can be daily driven yet track capable
cons: Poor factory sound from S55 engine - very raspy and rattly without modifications
No sync button for dual-zone climate control requiring separate adjustment of both sides
Crank hub failure issue requiring expensive $3000 fix even on unmodified cars
Mediocre electric steering feel compared to hydraulic steering
Average manual transmission feel from factory without modifications
expertReviews.verdict: After 2 years and 6000 additional miles, the owner still loves his 2018 F80 M3 Competition Package. While it has notable issues like poor factory sound, crank hub problems, and mediocre steering/transmission feel, these can be addressed with modifications. The car's stunning looks, strong community, and aftermarket support make it worthwhile. Owner has no plans to sell and considers it the best looking sports sedan ever made.

expertReviews.title: This is WHY the BMW F80 M3 is the BEST Car I've Ever Driven!
pros: Violent and aggressive DCT gearbox
Exceptional rear-wheel drive setup with proper M differential
Excellent traction with Michelin Pilot Sport 4S tires
Comfortable sporty bucket seats for long journeys
Aggressive engine sound and exhaust note
Track-capable dual purpose design
Carbon fiber roof and performance steering wheel
Full LED headlights transform front end appearance
cons: Will make other performance cars feel slow in comparison
Active sound system controversial compared to previous E92 M3
High power requires respect and proper handling
expertReviews.verdict: The reviewer is absolutely blown away by the F80 M3, calling it an 'absolute monster' and 'different league' compared to hot hatches. With around 425hp and violent DCT shifts, the car delivers exceptional performance and proper rear-wheel drive dynamics. The owner actively tracks the car at Nurburgring, proving its dual-purpose capability. Despite some controversy over sound vs previous generation, the reviewer considers this an aspirational dream car that transforms the driving experience.

expertReviews.title: 2016 BMW F80 M3 Review - Best M3 Generation When ...
pros: Significant power increase to 495 wheel horsepower with mods
Much more controllable than stock F80 with Euro MDM system
Excellent front-end response with suspension modifications
Beautiful Frozen Silver Metallic color (1 of 40)
Snappy 7-speed DCT transmission performance
Billstein with Swift Springs provides good ride quality
cons: Stock steering remains vague and numb with limited feedback
Peaky engine with non-linear throttle response
Brake pedal has poor initial bite and lacks progressiveness
Harsh ride quality over bumps with aftermarket bushings
Turbo lag can catch driver off guard when coming on boost
Still instills fear when driving hard compared to E92/E46 M3s
expertReviews.verdict: This heavily modified 2016 F80 M3 with 495 wheel horsepower demonstrates the platform's potential when properly upgraded. While the mods significantly improve controllability and performance over stock, fundamental issues like vague steering, peaky engine delivery, and poor brake feel remain. The reviewer still prefers E92 and E46 M3s overall but acknowledges this build gets 'really damn close' from a handling standpoint.
